  "market_context": "NASDAQ 15-minute chart approaches a daily fair value gap fill zone (~13000–13060) from above with sell-side liquidity resting just below the recent swing low, setting up a potential bullish reversal aligned with the daily bias.",
  "key_observation": "Price swept sell-side liquidity into the daily FVG fill, then aggressively shifted structure higher, retraced into discount/OTE where a small fair value gap was nested inside a bullish order block — a confluence entry zone aligned with the box setup.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified resting sell-side liquidity below the prior swing low as price moved into the daily FVG fill area.",
    "Step 2: Waited for the stop raid; confirmed price swept the SSL and reacted off the daily FVG.",
    "Step 3: Confirmed market structure shift when the next candle aggressively broke and closed above the prior high (displacement).",
    "Step 4: Applied a Fibonacci to the displacement leg to isolate the discount zone (below 0.5) and narrowed it down to the OTE (0.62–0.79).",
    "Step 5: Scanned the OTE for PD arrays and found a small fair value gap nested inside a down-close order block, also aligning with the box setup.",
    "Step 6: Placed entry at the nested FVG/OB confluence, stop below the swept low, first partial at nearby resistance, then targeted buy-side liquidity above.",
    "Step 7: Reviewed that, after partials, moving stop to break-even still allowed runners to reach the buy-side liquidity target."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade played out — first partial was hit, and price subsequently reached the buy-side liquidity target above.",
  "lessons": "Blending multiple PD arrays (FVG nested in OB at OTE within the box setup) at the same level improves risk-to-reward and confidence, but entry choice should balance R:R against the probability of being filled.",
